Formulas in R

Niels Richard Hansen

February 13, 2015

R provides a formula interface to linear models via the function lm and to generalized linear models via the function glm. That is, instead of specifying the matrix \(\mathbf{X}\) explicitly, it is derived from a formula. This is very convenient, and it allows us to focus on variables instead of how they are encoded as columns in \(\mathbf{X}\). It is, however, useful to know precisely how R interprets the formulas and translates them into matrices.

The matrix \(\mathbf{X}\) is known as the model matrix in R terminology. Internally to lm or glm the function model.matrix is used to create the model matrix from the formula and the data. We usually don’t need to call this function, but it is illustrative for understanding exactly how formulas are parsed.

Sample data

We simulate an example data set to work with.

set.seed(04022016)
b <- rnorm(150, 0)
c <- factor(sample(c(rep("A", 50), rep("B", 50), rep("C", 50))))
mu <- (c == "A") + cos(b) + 0.5 * (c == "B") * sin(b)
a <- rnorm(150, mu, 0.5)

And we plot the data. The right figure shows the data color coded according the groups encoded by the c variable, and the dashed curves are the true means within the three groups.

library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)
p1 <- qplot(b, a)
p2 <- qplot(b, a, color = c) + geom_line(aes(y = mu), linetype = 2) +
  theme(legend.position = "top")
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)

Question 1: Fit a linear regression model to data generated as above with a the response variable and b the predictor. Investigate the residuals. Does the model fit the data?

Model matrices

The linear regression model you fitted above was most likely fitted using lm with the formula a ~ b. This formula is used for the construction of a model matrix with two columns. A column of ones representing the intercept, and a column with the observed values of the predictor variable.

model.matrix(a ~ b)[1:10, ]
##    (Intercept)           b
## 1            1 -0.00976291
## 2            1 -1.64998340
## 3            1 -0.32014201
## 4            1 -1.42256848
## 5            1  1.24188519
## 6            1  1.08065770
## 7            1 -0.34586390
## 8            1  0.16357737
## 9            1  1.04708832
## 10           1  0.33458702

Question 2: How do you get rid of the intercept?**

If we “add” a factor on \(k\) levels the model matrix gets \(k-1\) additional columns. These are dummy variable encodings of the levels of the factor. The precise encoding is controlled by the contrasts.arg argument to model.matrix (the contrasts argument to lm or glm) or by setting the contrasts associated with a factor.

model.matrix(a ~ b + c)[1:10, ]
##    (Intercept)           b cB cC
## 1            1 -0.00976291  0  0
## 2            1 -1.64998340  0  1
## 3            1 -0.32014201  0  0
## 4            1 -1.42256848  0  0
## 5            1  1.24188519  0  0
## 6            1  1.08065770  1  0
## 7            1 -0.34586390  0  0
## 8            1  0.16357737  1  0
## 9            1  1.04708832  1  0
## 10           1  0.33458702  0  1
### We change the base level to be level 3 (value "C")
contrasts(c) <- contr.treatment(levels(c), base = 3)
model.matrix(a ~ b + c)[1:10, ]
##    (Intercept)           b cA cB
## 1            1 -0.00976291  1  0
## 2            1 -1.64998340  0  0
## 3            1 -0.32014201  1  0
## 4            1 -1.42256848  1  0
## 5            1  1.24188519  1  0
## 6            1  1.08065770  0  1
## 7            1 -0.34586390  1  0
## 8            1  0.16357737  0  1
## 9            1  1.04708832  0  1
## 10           1  0.33458702  0  0

A change of the dummy variable encoding does not change the model (the column space) only the parametrization. This may occasionally be useful for interpretation or for testing certain hypotheses.

Question 3: How can you check (numerically) that the two model matrices above span the same column space?

Interactions

In formulas, the arithmetic operators * and ^ together with : have special meanings.

  • Usage of b * c is equivalent b + c + b : c
  • Usage of b : c formulates the interaction model.
  • Usage of (a + b + c)^2 is equivalent to (a + b + c) * (a + b + c) is equivalent to a + b + c + a : b + a : c + b : c, etc.
model.matrix(a ~ c + b : c)[1:10, ]
##    (Intercept) cA cB        cA:b      cB:b      cC:b
## 1            1  1  0 -0.00976291 0.0000000  0.000000

Basis expansions

Transformations can be achieved by formally applying an R function to a variable in the formula specification. Expansions can be achieved if the R function returns a matrix and not a vector when applied to a vector.

library(splines)
model.matrix(a ~ ns(b, df = 4))[1:10, ]
##    (Intercept) ns(b, df = 4)1 ns(b, df = 4)2 ns(b, df = 4)3 ns(b, df = 4)4
